>Rewriting a dialog section for the 3rd time because I can't help but steer the conversation to weird aspects of the world
When I'm wholesale rewriting a section more than once, it means I'm not pacing right and/or connecting it meaningfully to the scene before and after.
This is why I hate inserting scenes when I'm still in the draft stage. They take 10x as long as when my outline is working right, but sometimes you need that scene to set up later events. Staying on that task is a PIA
>Literally a scene with other characters' wives talking with Freja about how to use marriage as tool to benefit peoples to foreshadow the events between Tribes and its Sequel.
As I've been advised elsewhere with my worldbuilding, how little can you get away with saying? How much would constitute an infodump? Can the conversation be dual-purposed to build character?
The funny thing is there's no one good answer. I've had complaints over a single, hundred word paragraph, yet also had people not blink at four thousand words of the same.
>Go on a tangent about fucking elves, of which will only feature at the very end of the story like fucking eagles in LoTR
I take great pains to avoid saying things simply because I don't need to show off everything. It's evolved into a quick bit of introduction where it makes sense to namedrop them.
I find the eagles are a bad example of bringing things up too early, and usually more of a sign that you're trying to railroad a massive plothole out of existence.
At least that's the case with me. My handwritten worldbuilding notes often look like conspiracy drivel.

>how to deal with it?
The other responses generally had good value, so pick and choose from those what fits for you.

I'll add something slightly different: Own the tangent(s). I mean, you may not want to do this for various reasons, but consider if the option has value. Example: you say the Elves only show up at the end? Feature more Elves and more Elf lore. Especially if you're setting the stage for them to be important after your story ends. Maybe you'll write more, maybe you won't. But if you flesh out Elves & their lore in your world, it allows the reader to imagine (better) what happens after the story concludes. This increases reader satisfaction by not leaving gaping questions open & unanswered.

Doesn't have to be specific or extensive. You can drop some of it in this conversation, and maybe insert a paragraph and a sentence occasionally while the story progresses. By the time the Elves show up, their backstory is more solid, you have less to present when they do show up, maybe you'll do another chapter or another story (or two) that will build on this.

How many words does it add to the current story? If you're talking an excess of 200 or 300, cutting them out may be more effort & trouble than it's worth (so long as they are done well to begin with). The value of leaving a little minor excess could outweigh the value of trimming.

So, Own It is an option and move on. If it's horribly annoying and disruptive, revisit it later and condense & trim. You'll probably have better perspective by then on what is important to publish and what is better in your personal notes for the world in your head canon.
